Aim:

Simulation of Washing Machine System

Theory:

A washing machine system is used in laundry services to process clothes through multiple stages such
as washing, rinsing, and spinning. Customers arrive with clothes for cleaning, and available washing
machines process them sequentially.

If all washing machines are busy, arriving clothes wait in a queue until a machine becomes available.

This simulation models a multiple-server laundry system with three washing machines and separate queues 
for each processing stage.

COMMANDS:
GENERATE
Creates clothes/customers entering the system.
QUEUE
Places customers into a waiting line.
ENTER
Allocates one available washing machine.
DEPART
Removes customers from the queue when processing begins.
ADVANCE
Simulates processing time.
LEAVE
Releases the washing machine after processing.
TERMINATE
Removes customers from the system or stops simulation.
STORAGE
Defines multiple washing machines/resources.
Scenario Overview:

The laundry service contains:

Three washing machines
Separate queues for washing, rinsing, and spinning
Sequential processing stages

Each customer undergoes:

Washing
Rinsing
Spinning

Customers wait whenever all washing machines are occupied.

The system behaves like a multi-stage multiple-server queueing system.

Key Components:
1. Customers (Clothes)

Clothes arrive randomly for laundry service.

2. Washing Machines (Servers)

Three washing machines process clothes simultaneously.

3. Queues

Separate waiting queues are maintained for:

Washing
Rinsing
Spinning
4. Processing Stages

Clothes pass through washing, rinsing, and spinning sequentially before leaving the system.

